{          INTRODUCTION          }
^-|CP||FP||ht|f|cp|8|AT|^B@2^Y@3
^B@2^*Bcaitlin: ^*N|cp||at|So What Do We Mean by ‘Reading the Opponents’ Cards?|
PG| ***** 1 ***** |


at|
As declarer we want to gather as much information about the opponents’ hands, especially if we have too many losers at a suit contract and/or not enough winners at notrump. What are these pieces of information? They are as follows:

A)     Bidding by an opponent who overcalls or makes a takeout double
B)     Bidding by an opponent who opens the bidding
C)     Bidding by an opponent who preempts: a two-level preempt places a known 6 cards, just as a three-level places 7 cards in that opponent’s hand
D)     Lack of bidding by an opponent whose partner opens the bidding, makes a takeout double or who overcalls.|
PG| ***** 2 ***** |


at|

What about information we get when an a opponent makes a lead?|
PG| ***** 3 ***** |


AT|

A)     The lead of the Ace (from AK), when neither declarer or dummy has the King, most often means the opponent on lead has the King.
B)     Assuming no doubleton lead, as with above, the lead of the King typically promises the Queen and the lead of Queen promises the Jack.
C)     If opponent leads the Queen and neither declarer nor dummy has the King, place it in the other opponent’s hand.|
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


AT|

The above is why we take our time before playing to the first trick and REVIEW THE BIDDING and ANALYZE THE LEAD. Both will give you invaluable information.
|
